{{multiple issues| {{notability|Products|date=August 2013}} {{refimprove|date=August 2013}} }} {{Infobox video game | title = Fruit Ninja: Puss in Boots | image = Fruit Ninja Puss in Boots.png | caption= ''Fruit Ninja: Puss in Boots'' logo | developer = [[Halfbrick Studios]] | publisher = | producer= [[DreamWorks]] | designer= | composer= | series = ''[[Fruit Ninja]]'' | engine = | released = October 20, 2011 | genre = [[Arcade game|Arcade]] | modes = | platforms = [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]] }} '''''Fruit Ninja: Puss in Boots''''' is a [[video game]] developed by [[Halfbrick Studios]]. A [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] from the highly successful ''[[Fruit Ninja]]'', it is also a crossover of the 2011 animated film ''[[Puss in Boots (2011 film)|Puss in Boots]]''. The game was released on October 20, 2011.<ref name="metacritic"/> Since the release of Halfbrick's Fruit Ninja 2.0 update, this game is no longer available for download.{{Citation needed|date=March 2017}}
==Gameplay== ''Fruit Ninja: Puss in Boots'' features two new modes (Desperado and Bandito) and The Stash, filled with unlockable wallpapers and blades. A fresh take on ''Fruit Ninja''{{’}}s Classic Mode, Desperado Mode features new Magic Beans and enhanced waves and scoring. Developed exclusively for ''Fruit Ninja: Puss in Boots'', Bandito Mode is a four-tiered challenge adventure where players must work through a number of increasingly difficult and varied slicing games. New "[[Puss in Boots (Shrek)|Puss in Boots]]" themed unlockable items available at The Stash include the Cat Cantina arena, the Firework blade and the Cat’s Claw.
==Reception== {{Video game reviews | MC = 79/100<ref name="metacritic">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/ios/fruit-ninja-puss-in-boots/critic-reviews |title=Fruit Ninja: Puss in Boots Critic Reviews for iPhone/iPad |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=5 August 2013}}</ref> | rev1 = ''[[TouchArcade]]'' | rev1Score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name="TouchArcade">{{cite web |url=https://toucharcade.com/2011/10/21/fruit-ninja-puss-in-boots-review/ |title='Fruit Ninja: Puss in Boots' Review – This Feline Fruit Fencer is a Great Addition to the Family |last=Campbell |first=Nissa |date=21 October 2011 |website=[[TouchArcade]] |accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref> }}
The game has received generally favourable reviews, with a [[Metacritic]] score of 79 out of 100 based on 12 reviews.<ref name="metacritic" /> ''[[TouchArcade]]'' said, "If you could only have one ''Fruit Ninja'' game on your phone, I'd tell you to keep the original. It has a lot more to offer. But ''Fruit Ninja: Puss in Boots'' is well worth playing, even if it's more expansion than stand-alone".<ref name="TouchArcade" /> ''AppSmile'' said, "While remaining very similar to its predecessor, the Puss In Boots version brings with it an exciting new game mode that makes the [[sequel]] a worthwhile pick-up".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.appsmile.com/2011/10/23/fruit-ninja-puss-in-boots-review/|title=Fruit Ninja: Puss In Boots Review|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2016}}</ref> [[IGN]] said, "Like ''[[Angry Birds Rio]]'', ''Fruit Ninja: Puss in Boots'' is a much better game than it needed to be. Pick it up!".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2011/10/25/fruit-ninja-puss-in-boots-review|title=Fruit Ninja: Puss in Boots Review|author=Justin Davis|date=25 October 2011|work=IGN|accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref> ''AppSpy'' said, "''Fruit Ninja: Puss in Boots'' shows how to make movie tie-in's work without being overbearing; Bandito mode brings a real Arcade flair to the original Fruit Ninja formula, while thematic touches give the game charm".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.appspy.com/review/4889/fruit-ninja-puss-in-boots-review|title=Fruit Ninja: Puss in Boots Review|author=Andrew Nesvadba|date=20 October 2011|work=appspy.com|accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref>
