[[Image:Hirajoshi scale on C Burrows.png|thumb|right|''Hirajoshi'' scale on C according to Burrows. {{audio|Hirajoshi scale on C Burrows.mid|Play}}]] [[Image:Hirajoshi scale on C Sachs & Slonimsky.png|thumb|right|''Hirajoshi'' scale on C according to Sachs and Slonimsky. {{audio|Hirajoshi scale on C Sachs & Slonimsky.mid|Play}}]] [[Image:Hirajoshi scale on C Kostka-Payne & Speed.png|thumb|right|''Hirajoshi'' scale on C according to Kostka & Payne and Speed. {{audio|Hirajoshi scale on C Kostka-Payne & Speed.mid|Play}}]]
'''''Hirajōshi'' scale''', or {{nihongo|''hira-choshi''|平調子|hirachōshi|lead=yes|extra=chōshi = tuning and hira = even, level, tranquil, standard or regular}} is a [[Musical tuning|tuning]] scale adapted from [[shamisen]] music by [[Yatsuhashi Kengyo|Yatsuhashi Kengyō]] for tuning of the ''[[koto (musical instrument)|koto]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Harich-Scheider|first=Eta|title=A History of Japanese Music|year=1973|origyear=1922|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=London|page=520|ISBN=0-19-316203-2}}</ref> "The ''hirajoshi'', ''kumoijoshi'', and ''kokinjoshi'' 'scales' are Western derivations of the koto tunings of the same names. These scales have been used by rock and jazz guitarists in search of 'new' sounds."<ref name="Speed">Speed, Burgess (2008). ''Japan: Your Passport to a New World of Music'', p.15. {{ISBN|978-0-7390-4303-5}}.</ref>
Burrows gives C-E-F{{music|#}}-G-B.<ref>Burrows, Terry (1999). ''How to Read Music'', p.90. {{ISBN|9780312241599}}.</ref> [[Curt Sachs|Sachs]],<ref>[[Leonard Meyer|Meyer, Leonard B.]] (1961). ''Emotion and Meaning in Music'', p.224. {{ISBN|978-0-226-52139-8}}.</ref> as well as [[Nicolas Slonimsky|Slonimsky]],<ref>Nicolas Slonimsky, (1947). ''Thesaurus of Scales and Musical Patterns'', pg. 160</ref> give C-D{{music|b}}-F-G{{music|b}}-B{{music|b}}. Speed<ref name="Speed"/> and Kostka & Payne<ref>Kostka & Payne (1995). ''Tonal Harmony'', p.484. Third Edition. {{ISBN|0-07-300056-6}}.</ref> give C-D-E{{music|b}}-G-A{{music|b}}. Note that all are [[anhemitonic scale|hemitonic]] [[pentatonic scale]]s (five note scales with one or more [[semitone]]s) and are different modes of the same pattern of intervals, 2-1-4-1-4 semitones.
The five [[mode (music)|modes]] of ''hirajoshi'' can also be derived as subsets of the [[Ionian mode|Ionian]], [[Phrygian mode|Phrygian]], [[Lydian mode|Lydian]], [[Aeolian mode|Aeolian]], and [[Locrian mode|Locrian]] modes.{{citation needed|date=June 2012}}
Synonymous scales have different names per region of Japan, as well as according to several ethnomusicologists and researchers, which may lead to some confusion. For example, the [[Iwato scale|''Iwato'' scale]] bears the same intervals as Slonimsky's concept of the ''Hirajoshi'' scale, and is also the fourth mode of the [[In scale|''In'' scale]]. The same scale given by Kostka & Payne matches the third mode of the ''In'' scale.
==See also== * [[In scale]] * [[Japanese mode]] * [[Japanese musical scales]]
