'''Moi-Yo Miller''' was the stage name of '''Mona Loretta Miller''' (24 April 1914 – 7 October 2018),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geelongadvertiser.com.au/article/2009/10/05/109295_news_pf.html|title=Sim Sala Bim: It's Moi-Yo magic|accessdate=2 October 2010|quote=She was born Mona Loretta Miller in 1914, the start of World War 1.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geelongadvertiser.com.au/news/geelong/geelongborn-illusionist-moiyo-miller-dies-aged-104/news-story/b47b282cf24fcf55f402955aec0b203a|title=Geelong-born illusionist Moi-Yo Miller dies aged 104|last=Ryan|first=Jemma|date=|website=www.geelongadvertiser.com.au|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-10-11}}</ref> an Australian entertainer who toured the world as a [[magician's assistant]] and illusionist of the stage magician [[Harry August Jansen|Dante]] (a.k.a. Harry Jansen), during the [[Magic (illusion)|Golden Age of Magic]] of the 1930s and 1940s<ref name="pictureaus">{{cite web|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.cs-pa-http%253A%252F%252Fwww.slv.vic.gov.au%252Falma%252F0%252F0%252F0%252Fdoc%252Fal000616.shtml|title=Dante on stage with Moi-Yo Miller|publisher=National Picture Library of Australia|accessdate=9 April 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080918223946/http://nla.gov.au/nla.cs-pa-HTTP%253A%252F%252FWWW.SLV.VIC.GOV.AU%252FALMA%252F0%252F0%252F0%252FDOC%252FAL000616.SHTML|archivedate=18 September 2008}}</ref>

==Biography==
Miller was born in  [[Geelong, Victoria|Geelong]]<ref name="pictureaus"/> She first met [[Harry August Jansen|Dante]] (aka Harry Jansen) while still in her late teens when she was appearing in a musical revue in Melbourne. Dante had decided to recruit an Australian girl as an assistant after, in his words, "he saw in Melbourne more beautiful women per square block than he had seen in any other part of the World".<ref name="kingofmagicians">{{cite web|url=http://www.kingofmagicians.com/moiyo.htm|title=Australia's Most Beautiful Woman With Dante: Miss Moi-yo Miller|publisher=kingofmagicians|accessdate=9 April 2009}}</ref> 

Miller dated Dante's son, Bill, and went on to work with Dante, staying with him for the rest of his performing career. She very quickly became his main assistant and an integral part of his show ''Sim Sala Bim''. She was often billed as "Australia's Most Beautiful Woman".<ref name="kingofmagicians"/> She once estimated that she had been sawed in half around 11,800 times during her career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxxneon.com/reviews/womeninboxes.htm|title=Reviews...Women in Boxes|publisher=MasterMath|accessdate=9 April 2009}}</ref>

Miller became highly regarded among professional magic performers and is widely cited as one of the all-time great magic assistants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.magictricks.com/library/histwomen.htm|title=Women In Magic|publisher=magictricks.com|accessdate=9 April 2009}}</ref> She features in the 2008 documentary movie, ''Women in Boxes'', which explores the vital role of assistants in magic.<ref name="womeninboxes">{{cite web|url=http://www.womeninboxes.com/cast.htm|title=''Women in Boxes''|publisher=WIB LLC|accessdate=9 April 2009}}</ref><ref>{{IMDb title|id=1268991|title=Women in Boxes|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> In 1993 she received the Dragon Award presented by the J. Marberger Stuart Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dragonaward.org/Moi-Yo1993.html|title=1993 Dragon Award - Moi Yo Miller and Arturo Montes|publisher=J. Marberger Stuart Foundation|accessdate=9 April 2009}}</ref> She celebrated her 100th birthday in 2014.<ref>[http://www.kingofmagicians.com/Moi%20Yo%20Birthday.html Happy 100th Birthday Moi Yo Miller]</ref> A public art mural of Miller’s face was created by artist Michael Cassar in June 2016 on the corner of James St and Minns Lane, Geelong.

