{{Infobox person | name = Rollin Howard | image =Rollin Howard wench.jpg | image_size = | caption = | birth_date = c. 1840 | birth_place = [[New York City]] | death_date = June 19, 1879 (about age 39) | death_place = | occupation = Actor, Minstrel show performer | spouse = | parents = | children = }}
'''Rollin Howard''' (1840 - June 19, 1879) was an [[United States|American]] [[minstrel show|minstrel]] performer, best known for his female [[blackface]] impersonations.
Howard was born as '''Ebenezer G.B. Holder''' in [[New York City]] around 1840, and appeared in minstrel productions from approximately 1860 to 1870. He appeared in other dramatic performances both before and after his minstrel period.<ref name="monarchs">Rice, Edward Le Roy. [https://books.google.com/books?id=nvY5AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA128 Monarchs of minstrelsy, from "Daddy" Rice to date], p. 127-28 (1911)</ref> After the [[American Civil War]], female impersonators became more common in minstrel shows, and Howard was considered one of the leading performers in such roles, along with [[Francis Leon]] and Eugene d'Amelie.<ref name="cross">Ferris, Lesley. [https://books.google.com/books?id=HsnKh0lTEHEC&pg=PA86 Crossing the stage: controversies on cross-dressing], p. 86 (1993)</ref>
[[Image:Howard and Griffin wench.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Rollin Howard (in wench costume) and George Griffin]] Among songs that Howard performed, he was credited with "arranging" on one of the first sheet music publications for ''[[Shoo Fly, Don't Bother Me]]'' in 1869.<ref name="shoo1">Sanjek, Russell. [https://books.google.com/books?id=7UbS22L6neQC&pg=PA372 American Popular Music and Its Business: From 1790 to 1909], p. 371-72 (1988)</ref> The song was extremely popular, and though the exact authorship is not clear, at times Howard has received some authorship credit.<ref name="howardaut1">(1 August 1902). [http://texashistory.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metapth85958/m1/4/ Stories of Famous Songs], ''Houston Daily Post'' ("Shoo Fly Don't Bodder Me which was once credited to [[Thomas Brigham Bishop|T. Brigham Bishop]] the old minstrel, was written according to [[Charles "Charlie" White|White's]] diary by Rollin Howard ....")</ref><ref name="detroit1">(30 August 1872). [https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/freep/access/1880946412.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+30%2C+1872&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+%281858-1922%29&desc=PERSONAL&pqatl=google Personal], ''Detroit Free Press'' ("Rollin Howard, author of the famous song "Shoo Fly," has gone to Europe.")</ref> {{Clear}}
